.alert.alert-info
  Genotype data needs to be provided in one of the accepted formats -
  #{link_to 'VCF', 'http://samtools.github.io/hts-specs/', title: 'Variant Call Format', target: "_blank"},
  #{link_to 'HapMap', 'http://augustogarcia.me/statgen-esalq/Hapmap-and-VCF-formats-and-its-integration-with-onemap/#hapmap', title: "HapMap", target: "_blank"} or
  #{link_to 'CSV', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comma-separated_values', title: 'Comma-separated values', target: "_blank"}.
  %br
  %br
  VCF and HapMap are well-defined formats and any such file should be acceptable. However, for best performance low quality
  or irrelevant data should be filtered out of the VCF file before it is uploaded.
  %br
  %br
  Unlike VCF, the CSV format itself does not exactly determine how the
  data should be formatted. As such, we provide a <b>#{analysis_data_file_template_link(:gwas_genotype)}</b>
  showing expected data layout:
  %br
  %br

  %ul
    %li Values in the CSV file must be comma-delimited.
    %li
      First column of the CSV file is an ID column. Values in this column denote the <b>
      #{link_to "SNP", 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-nucleotide_polymorphism', title: 'Single-nucleotide polymorphism'}</b>s.
      (e.g. rs17602729, snp-1, mut_a123). SNP identifiers must be unique.

    %li
      Each following column is associated with a <b>sample</b>.

      Value in the header row identifies the sample (e.g. p-00001, su_hri96_DEU146_BRA_00018_001),
      whereas values in subsequent rows denote number of alleles affected (0, 1, 2 or NA). Sample identifiers
      must be unique.
